            NAME 
            make.symbol - Draws a graphic symbol or character on the map
            composition at a point location in a MAPGEN sites file.
            
            SYNOPSIS
            make.symbol [filename]
            
            DESCRIPTION 
            make.symbol constructs map symbols at point locations from 
            MAPGEN sites files in the sites_geo directory.  GRASS sites,
            attribute, or category files can be used and are converted
            to a MAPGEN sites file during this process.  If given,
            [filename] is used for the name of the overlay file
            generated.
            
            Appendix III of the MAPGEN User Manual displays the
            characters or symbols available in the currently supported
            fonts.
            
            The user is required to provide the following:
            
                 - MAPGEN sites file name (and GRASS element and
                      name)
                 - overlay file name (if not specified in the command
                      line)
                 - map definition file name
                 - plotter pen number
                 - symbol font
                 - symbol number
                 - symbol size
                 - legend text for symbol
            
            Completing the response sequence generates the required
            files to construct the map element.  Definition parameters
            are stored in the symbols directory; graphic elements to
            draw the map on the screen or plotter are stored in the ovm 
            directory.  The default file name for both directories is
            the site file name, suffixed with ".s", where s denotes a
            symbol file.
            
            Changing the appearance of the symbol (e.g. symbol size or
            number, pen, etc.) can be done by regenerating the
            make.symbol command and overwriting the initial file, or by
            editing the text definition file, and using the redo.symbol
            command.
            
                 (edit) example:          vi symbols/[filename]
                                          vi symbols/archsites.s

